{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18462"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75892"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11191"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61405"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5660"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75892"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Public Health and Wellbeing Act 2008 establishes requirements for medical practitioners to notify public health authorities about certain infectious diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the notification requirements for medical practitioners under this Act?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All infectious diseases must be reported within 24 hours","Telephone notification alone is sufficient for urgent conditions","Urgent conditions require immediate telephone notification and written notification within 5 days","Notification is only required for hospital-acquired infections","Written notification is required within 14 days for all conditions"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnder the Public Health and Wellbeing Act 2008, \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent conditions require immediate telephone notification and written notification within 5 days\u003C/strong\u003E. This dual notification system ensures prompt public health action for serious infectious diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile pathology laboratories are also required to notify the health department of positive results for notifiable conditions, medical practitioners must still fulfill their notification obligations independently, particularly for urgent conditions where immediate public health action may be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Eall infectious diseases must be reported within 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because only specified notifiable conditions require reporting, and different timeframes apply based on urgency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe claim that \u003Cstrong\u003Etelephone notification alone is sufficient for urgent conditions\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because written notification is also mandatory within 5 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Enotification is only required for hospital-acquired infections\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because notification requirements apply to all specified infectious diseases regardless of where they were acquired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Ewritten notification is required within 14 days for all conditions\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the mandated timeframe for written notification is 5 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of urgent conditions include \u003Cem\u003EVibrio cholerae\u003C/em\u003E, measles, and meningococcal infection. Routine conditions like chlamydia and hepatitis B require only written notification within 5 days.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Public Health and Wellbeing Act 2008 requires notification of specified infectious diseases to the Department of Health within specified timeframes.","Urgent conditions must be reported immediately by telephone and in writing within 5 days.","Routine conditions must be reported in writing within 5 days of diagnosis.","Both medical practitioners and pathology laboratories have notification obligations under the Act."],"references":["Public Health and Wellbeing Act 2008. Victoria Health. Available from: https://www.health.vic.gov.au/legislation/public-health-and-wellbeing-act-2008"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61405"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61405"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T12:12:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T12:13:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11191"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75892"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0